<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> ride high • ride tall</xh5><p> <i>ride high</i>—(also: ride high in the saddle) 1. have a period of success, popularity, etc.: The new government has been <u>riding high</u> in the polls for several months now. 2. <i>(of a boat)</i> sit high in the water: It was made of welded aluminum, stuffed with plenty of lightweight Styrofoam to make the boat <u>ride high</u> in the water. <i>Cf.: ride low</i>—(of a boat) sit low in the water: Ballast water may also be carried so that a ship <u>rides low</u> enough in the water to pass under bridges.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>ride high on the hog</b>—(coll., also: live high on the hog) live in a lavish or extravagant manner: Oh, yes, sometimes you <u>ride high on the hog</u>, but most of the time, you settle for the limits the world has placed on you.</p><p><i>ride tall</i>—(also: walk tall) show dignity and self-respect: Doesn’t matter if you eat corn mash and saddle your own horse; you can still <u>ride tall</u>.</p> </entry>
